snippet.textDisplay: Gift giving in Japan is such that with the average living space not affording TONS of room for knick knacks and tchatchkes, and the quality of being ephemeral being valued due to religious influences, edible gifts are much more common there. So I can see what would give gold leaf instant coffee a bit more appeal there. That's the culture that gives rise to those viral pictures people post of 9,000 yen (~$90) boxes of fruit. If you have someone important to impress or a very formal family gathering, the best of the best fruit is considered a very elegant gift, one that provides an experience and contributes to the health of the receiver. I think even given all this, the instant coffee is a bit gaudy. A classier gift would be a high quality tin of loose leaf tea or a super high quality tin of instant coffee, or a decorative canister to hold either one.

snippet.textDisplay: I want the damned bread. The £30 version not the £200 one. (It’s only £140 today, btw.) I went to his Italian site directly and saw that the 1kg loaves are in fact @ $30 but the shipping to the US is $35 (per loaf!) so that’s a hard no. There is one in San Francisco that’s supposedly good but I refuse to support anything Giada likes. Nothing more pretentious than over-pronouncing every third word. Venda Ravioli here I come! (An Italian grocer in Providence, RI that imports burrata from Italy every Wednesday.) Yeah, I hear it now. Don’t care. It’s delicious and they’re going to have that bread…

snippet.textDisplay:
Pheasant got it's posh characterization from being imported strictly for feudal lords or the king to hunt and eat. It would not have been on the menu for regular folks, because to get it you would have to poach them and that was punishable by death. This changed after the feudal system broke down, so I was happy they didn't rule it posh.
When I was a child, my dad hunted. We never considered game birds or other types of venison 'fancy', they were just food.

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys Esthechoc makes bold claims it can't back up. The Advertising Standards Authority in the UK actually told them to stop making the health/anti-ageing claims as the 'facts' aren't approved by the EU's food safety register, and they can't provide adequate evidence to uphold them. Nevertheless they continue to imply there are benefits absolutely everywhere they can, while 'the science' section of their website is curiously broken...


Just wanted to let you know. Faux science is rampant online & in the media and it can be really hard to notice. But I think if you look into it, paying £30 for something that might work, but also might harm you, or do nothing at all that apparently also tastes bad is... silly.

Love the episode!
